subSubSection.paragraph:
Description of male:
Body (
Fig. 705
) slender, compressed laterally. Fastigium of vertex (
Fig. 601
) short and wide, slightly depressed and sloping. Frontal ridge slightly narrowed just below the median ocellus. Vertex (
Fig. 601
) narrow, 1.3 times narrower than vertical diameter and very slightly narrower than transversal diameter of eye; supraocular foveola distinct, open 
type
, semiclosed in some males; median carinula long and grooved; convex in lateral view. Antennae with 12 segments. Pronotum (
Figs. 601
, 
705
) compressed laterally, roof-shaped; lateral carinae weak, more distinct in metazona of some males; median carina slightly raised, with distinct longitudinal sulcus, wider in anterior part; slightly convex or straight in lateral view. Anterior margin of prosternum raised collar-like with a blunt median projection, in some males tridentate or tongue-shaped but never sharply pointed. Mesosternal interspace 2.2 times wider than its length and clearly narrower than mesosternal lobes. Hind femur (
Fig. 705
) 2.6 times longer than its height, proximal part widened and sharply narrowing towards genicular lobes, dorsal margin straight in proximal part, then sloping backwards, finelly serrated; ventral margin convex. Hind tibia with 9 inner, 9–11 outer spines. Abdominal tergites (
Fig. 705
) simple; median carina very slightly raised, not protruded posteriorly. Mesonotum and metanotum with grooved median carinae. Tympanum absent. Arch of zygoma narrow; posterior lobes of zygoma relatively short and narrow; apodemes narrow with distinct apical notch; pseudolophi separated with 10–13 spines.
